In other words, if the sensor L 2  binds 100 times more loosely to calcium than L 1 , one needs to add 10 times more sensor ( L 0,2  = 110 nM) in the cell to have the same (low) amount of Ca 2+  bound. Of course, higher sensor concentrations are not ideal because of the potential toxicity to the cells.

Also, with the tighter-bound sensor L 1 , the fraction of the bound sensor is 10/11.01 = 91%, while with L 2  it is 9%. Thus, for the first sensor, Δ F/F 0  (Eq.  4 ) is higher than for the second one, which means that the imaging contrast with L 1  is higher. Hence, in theory, it is better to have a tight binding ( K d  lower than the Ca 2+  concentration to measure) to minimize the amount of sensor needed and its toxicity, while maximizing contrast in imaging.
